ELK Lab (Fedora) – Quick Setup
1. Install Elasticsearch & Kibana
sudo rpm --import https://artifacts.elastic.co/GPG-KEY-elasticsearch

sudo tee /etc/yum.repos.d/elasticsearch.repo <<EOF
[elasticsearch]
name=Elasticsearch
baseurl=https://artifacts.elastic.co/packages/8.x/yum
gpgcheck=1
gpgkey=https://artifacts.elastic.co/GPG-KEY-elasticsearch
enabled=1
type=rpm-md
EOF

sudo dnf install elasticsearch kibana -y
sudo systemctl enable --now elasticsearch
sudo systemctl enable --now kibana

2. (Optional) Disable security for easy local use

Elasticsearch (/etc/elasticsearch/elasticsearch.yml):

xpack.security.enabled: false
xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: false


Kibana (/etc/kibana/kibana.yml):

xpack.security.enabled: false


Restart:

sudo systemctl restart elasticsearch
sudo systemctl restart kibana


Open Kibana:

http://localhost:5601

3. Generate sample logs

Run:

python3 generate_pipeline_logs.py


This creates pitchquest_pipeline.log.

4. Load logs into Kibana

In Kibana:
Management → Upload File → Select pitchquest_pipeline.log
